Date: 17 Nov 2012
Source: Deccan Chronicle [edited]
http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/cities/bengaluru/anthrax-fear-dies-out-big-cats-safe-now-972


Anthrax fear dies out, big cats safe for now
--------------------------------------------
The tiger reserves in the state are no more under the threat of the deadly anthrax virus [sic], as the spores detected in Thalavadi forest range of Sathyamangalam Forest Division on the Tamil Nadu border have died away.

The alert sounded at Bandipur Tiger Reserve and Biligiri Ranganatha Swamy (BRT) forests under the Kollegal Forest Division, which borders Sathyamangalam, have been withdrawn. An elephant calf was found dead on 8 Nov 2013 near Kodapampalli Thoddi village in Thalavadi range and the [necropsy] revealed that the elephant died due to anthrax. It had created a scare among forest officials of Tamil Nadu and Karnataka, as anthrax is known to wipe out wildlife once it strikes.

"It is nearly 10 days since the elephant calf died because of anthrax. No other animal has been found suffering from the [bacillus], and it is unlikely that there could be any more cases. We had constituted multiple monitoring teams to track the movement of elephants. The teams have not come across any animal found weak or suffering from anthrax. Generally, any elephant that is infected gets isolated and becomes weak within a few days," said N. Satish, Deputy Forest Officer, Sathyamangalam Division.

The official said they followed all necessary procedures while disposing the elephant carcass. Water bodies in the area were chlorinated and ring vaccination was carried out among cattle to stop the spread of [disease]. "We were successful in our attempt and the anthrax spores have died away," he said.

Mr Ajai Mishra, CCF (Project Elephant), said: "Our monitoring teams have not found anything worrying."

[Byline: S.V. Krishna Chaitanya]

