[I apologise for the lateness of this posting but somehow it got shuffled into my "Junk" folder. The moral of this is to check your junk file every few days even if it seems to be 100 percent junk. How this young elephant got infected is still unclear. But one must applaud the park authorities for taking it very seriously and actively searching for other cases, which, fortunately, have not appeared, as well as vaccinating nearby cattle.

To find the Sathyamangalam Forest and Wildlife Sanctuary, go to:
http://wikimapia.org/18484274/Sathyamangalam-forests or
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sathyamangalam_Wildlife_Sanctuary. The sanctuary is home to some 850 Indian elephants, making it the the largest elephant habitat in the country.

I have a request of those of you who read the Anthrax Postings: Rob Fairley, a veterinary pathologist in Christchurch, New Zealand, is in need of fixed tissue from an anthrax case or cases so he can train his eye for what he should be looking for in case that this disease might have slide under the radar into his country. The last recorded case of anthrax in New Zealand was in 1954. And he has no personal experience of this disease when he was working previously as a veterinary pathologist in California and Saskatchewan. If any of you can help him with tissue blocks, or stained or unstained slides, his e-mail address is: Rob Fairley <Rob.Fairley@gribbles.co.nz>. Thank you. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/2kP3.]
